	"explanation4": {
		"component": "Explanation",
		"content": [
			"<p><b>1. A bit about verbs in French:</b></p><p>There are three groups of regular verbs in French. The biggest of these is called the -er group, simply because the infinitive ends with the letters -er. Parler (to speak), habiter (to live), chanter (to sing), danser (to dance) are examples of - er verbs.</p><p><b>NB</b> There is only <b>ONE present tense</b> in French, so you translate je parle either as 'I speak' or 'I am speaking' depending on the context.</p><table><thead><tr><th><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/parler.mp3'>parler</span></th><th>to speak</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/je parle.mp3'>je parle</span></td><td>I speak / am speaking</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/tu parles.mp3'>tu parles</span></td><td>you speak / are speaking</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/il parle.mp3'>il parle</span></td><td>he / it speaks / is speaking</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/elle parle.mp3'>elle parle</span></td><td>she / it speaks / is speaking</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/nous parlons.mp3'>nous parlons</span></td><td>we speak / are speaking</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/vous parlez.mp3'>vous parlez</span></td><td>you speak / are speaking</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/ils parlent.mp3'>ils parlent</span></td><td>they speak / are speaking</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/elles parlent.mp3'>elles parlent</span></td><td>they speak / are speaking</td></tr></tbody></table><p>venir is a common irregular verb.</p><p><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/venir de.mp3'>venir de</span> to come from</p><table><tbody><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/je viens.mp3'>je viens</span> (de Marseille)</td><td>I come (from Marseille)...</td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/tu viens.mp3'>tu viens</span></td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/il vient.mp3'>il vient</span></td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/elle vient.mp3'>elle vient</span></td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/nous venons.mp3'>nous venons</span></td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/vous venez.mp3'>vous venez</span></td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/ils viennent.mp3'>ils viennent</span></td></tr><tr><td><span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/elles viennent.mp3'>elles viennent</span></td></tr></tbody></table>",
			"<p><b>2 De</b></p><p><b>NB</b> The word de occurs in French with a variety of meanings. Here it means from, and it's followed by a place name. Look at the following examples illustrating the forms:</p><p>Je viens <span style='color: red;'><b>de</b></span> Paris (for towns, cities, villages)</p><p>Je viens <span style='color: green;'><b>de</b></span> Belgique (for feminine countries and regions beginning with a consonant)</p><p>Je viens <span style='color: black;'><b>d'</b></span>Angleterre (for all singular place names beginning with a vowel or mute h)</p><p>Je viens <span style='color: cyan;'><b>du</b></span> Canada (for masculine countries and regions beginning with a consonant)</p><p>Je viens <span style='color: purple;'><b>des</b></span> Seychelles (for plural countries)</p>",
			"<p><b>3 Feminine forms of professions and adjectives</b></p><p>When describing a female or any feminine noun, you will often see the addition of a letter or letters to the original masculine noun or adjective.</p><ul><li>If the ending is <b>e</b> there is no addition: both masculine and feminine are the the same e.g. <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/célibataire.mp3'>célibataire</span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/journaliste.mp3'>journaliste</span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/serbe.mp3'>serbe</span> etc.</li><li>If the last letter is a consonant, then generally <b>e</b> is added to form the feminine e.g. <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/étudiant.mp3'>étudiant</span> (m) <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/étudiante.mp3'>étudiante</span> (f), <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/chinois.mp3'>chinois</span> (m), <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/chinoise.mp3'>chinoise</span> (f) <b>NB</b> <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/médecin.mp3'>médecin</span> is an exception – this is for both a male and female doctor.</li><li>If the final letter is <b>é</b>, then an <b>e</b> is added for the feminine e.g.  <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/marié.mp3'>marié</span> (m), <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/mariée.mp3'>mariée</span> (f)</li><li>If the ending is <b>en</b>, <b>ne</b> is added for the feminine e.g. <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/informaticien.mp3'>informaticien</span> (m) / <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/informaticienne.mp3'>informaticienne</span> (f), <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/australien.mp3'>australien</span> (m), <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/australienne.mp3'>australienne</span> (f)</li></ul>"
		],
		"id": "explanation4",
		"titleText": "Grammar / Use of Language"
	},
	"explanation5": {
		"component": "LO3Demystify",
		"content": [
			"<p><b>To sound or not to sound?</b></p><ol><li><p>The third person verb ending <b>ent</b> is never pronounced. <img src='/images/shh.jpg' style='vertical-align: middle;' alt='lady with finger to lips. Shh' title='lady with finger to lips. Shh'/> e.g. <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/Ils parlent.mp3'>Ils parl<b><u>ent</u></b></span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/elles chantent.mp3'>elles chant<b><u>ent</u></b></span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/ils dansent.mp3'>ils dans<b><u>ent</u></b></span></p></li><li><p>Usually, the consonants <b>d</b>, <b>g</b>, <b>p</b>, <b>s</b>, <b>t</b>, <b>x</b>, <b>z</b> are silent when they are the last letter of the word. However, these are sounded when the next word begins with a vowel or mute h. This is known as making a liaison. </p><p>Compare these: <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/les professeurs.mp3'>les professeurs</span> / <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/les étudiants.mp3'>le<b>s é</b>tudiants</span> – <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/il est français.mp3'>il est français</span> / <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/il est anglais.mp3'>il es<b>t a</b>nglais</span> - <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/un grand poète.mp3'>un grand poète</span> / <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/un grand homme.mp3'>un gran<b>d ho</b>mme</span></p></li><li><p>The sound : 'eh'</b></p></li></ol><p>Listen to the following:  <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/vous parlez.mp3'>vous parl<b>ez</b></span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/il est américain.mp3'>il <b>est</b> am<b>é</b>ricain</span> <b>et</b> <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/je suis ghanéenne.mp3'>je suis ghan<b>é</b>enne</span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/elle est mariée.mp3'>elle <b>est</b> mari<b>ée</b></span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/nous sommes fiancés.mp3'>nous sommes fianc<b>és</b></span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/elles sont fatiguées.mp3'>elles sont fatigu<b>ées</b></span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/écouter.mp3'><b>é</b>cout<b>er</b></span>, <span class='audio-link' sound-file='/sounds/fr/regarder.mp3'>regard<b>er</b></span></p><p>You will notice that <b>-et</b>, <b>-ez</b>, <b>é</b>, <b>-ée</b>, <b>-és</b>, <b>-ées</b> and  also <b>-er</b> as an infinitive ending are all pronounced the same, as are  the words <b>est</b> and <b>es</b>.</p>"
		],
		"id": "explanation5",
		"titleText": "Demystifying French Pronunciation"
	},
